// ch05 §5.5/ch01 §1.1 list "indirection through, or pointer arithmetic
// on, a value of pointer type" together as one gated operation, implying
// `*(p + 1)` (dereferencing the result of pointer arithmetic) should be
// legal inside `[[scpp::unsafe]] { }`, exactly like bare `*p`. As
// currently implemented, though, dereference only supports a plain
// local raw-pointer/unique_ptr variable or a captured field of one --
// not a subscript or any other expression -- so this is rejected with
// "dereference ('*') currently only supports a plain local
// std::unique_ptr or raw pointer variable...". A narrower gap than
// documented; worth checking again once pointer arithmetic composes with
// dereference.
int main() {
    int x = 5;
    int* p = &x;
    [[scpp::unsafe]] {
        return *(p + 0);
    }
}
